        ## Anatomy

        {image here}

        ### Dialog
        The dialog contains three primary elements. First, the `.spirit-dialog` container with a unique dialog id. Second, the `.spirit-dialog__overlay` container to display a darkened background behind the dialog. Third, the `.spirit-dialog__dialog` container that has within the visual content of the dialog.

        ### Close Button (optional)
        When a close button is used, it is an [Icon Only](/components/buttons.html#icon-only) button. Depending on the dialog type (see below), the close button can either be the first element within the `.spirit-dialog__dialog` and displayed outside the dialog content area, or can be within the `.spirit-dialog__header` (see below). The close icon has attribute `data-a11y-dialog-hide` and `aria-label=”Close Dialog”` and uses the Spirit `x` icon .

        ### Header (optional)
        When a header is used, the `.spirit-dialog__header` is the first element within the `.spirit-dialog__dialog.` Within this header, a `.spirit-dialog__header-title` is required. Optionally, a container `.spirt-dialog__header-icons` can be used to house a close or other action [Icon Only](/components/buttons.html#icon-only) buttons.

        ### Content
        The dialog’s primary content is always contained within the `.spirit-dialog__content` element.

        ### Footer (optional)
        If primary action items or other information is needed below the content of the dialog, an optional `.spirit-dialog__footer` is used.

        ### Trigger (optional)
        A trigger (i.e. button, card, other interactive element) can be used to trigger the display of a dialog. To automatically target the dialog by clicking on the trigger, the trigger must have the attribute `data-a11y-dialog-show=”dialog-id”` containing the unique id of the targeted dialog container (`.spirit-dialog`). For other methods of triggering the dialog, see [Guidelines - JavaScript](/#).

        ## Simple

        Use when displaying information that does not require a user action, such as a read-only document or a supplemental video.
